[4] USA: Ebola Aid Workers Still Avoiding New York and New Jersey, USA
Date: Thu 1 Jan 2015
Source: NPR [edited]
http://www.npr.org/blogs/health/2015/01/01/374194902/ebola-aid-workers-still-avoiding-new-york-and-new-jersey


State officials in New Jersey (NJ) and New York (NY) explain the [Ebola quarantine] rules as: A health care worker who treated Ebola patients can serve his/her mandatory quarantine at home in NJ or in NY. If you don't live in those 2 states -- and you have no symptoms that suggest you might have Ebola -- you will be allowed to pass through the airport, and return to wherever you live.

But some international aid groups "don't want people to be quarantined unnecessarily," says Margaret Aguirre of International Medical Corps, based in Los Angeles [California]. Her group has been telling returning health care workers to avoid JFK [in NY] and Newark [in NJ] airports.

The International Medical Corps isn't the only aid group that's been avoiding New York and New Jersey, travel-wise. "We're having to make sure that our people coming back from Liberia don't go through those 2 states," says Franklin Graham, president of Samaritan's Purse. "We've got to bring them in some other way -- get them into Washington through Dulles [in Virginia], or Atlanta [Georgia], someplace like that."

Other states and municipalities have adopted a patchwork of regulations; many of these rules go beyond what's recommended by the federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC). The CDC says most returning health care workers should monitor themselves for 21 days -- but they don't need to be isolated unless they start showing symptoms. ... -- more

[Byline: Joel Rose]

