[5] UN: Outgoing head of UN Ebola mission sums up progress in 'big battle' with outbreak
Date: Fri 2 Jan 2015
Source: UN News Centre [edited]
http://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=49726


Outgoing head of the United Nations Mission for Ebola Emergency Response (UNMEER), Anthony Banbury today [2 Jan 2015] pointed to significant progress in tackling the outbreak since he was appointed in September last year [2014], while stressing that zero cases is the only acceptable outcome in the "big battle" with the disease.

As Mr. Banbury prepares to hand over the reins of UNMEER to Ismail Ould Cheikh Ahmed on Saturday [3 Jan 2015], he was able to point to the latest World Health Organization (WHO) report on the epidemic, which counted 20 206 confirmed, probable or suspected cases of Ebola and 7905 reported deaths [instead of 1.4 million as predicted in September 2014].

His last trip to review progress in the 3 most affected countries of Guinea, Liberia and Sierra Leone revealed an increased number of isolation beds in all 3 countries, with 2 beds per patient in Guinea, 3.5 in Sierra Leone, and 14 in Liberia.

With support from UNMEER and other partners, all 3 countries also have capacity sufficient to isolate and treat 100 per cent of confirmed Ebola patients and enough burial teams to ensure safe and dignified burials for 100 per cent of all deaths due to the disease.

Despite the progress, Mr. Banbury said several challenges remain, including the geographical dispersion of Ebola. There was also a need to change community behaviours and reduce resistance to the massive interventions attempted. "We are engaged in a big battle with this disease," he said. "It's an insidious, invasive disease that attacks people through acts of caring and kindness. ... It's going to be extremely hard for us to bring it down to zero but that is what we will do. That is the only acceptable outcome." ... -- more

