[6] Asia: Where could Ebola strike next? Scientists virus hunt in Asia
Date: Fri 2 Jan 2015
Source: NPR [edited]
http://www.npr.org/blogs/goatsandsoda/2015/01/02/371994171/where-could-ebola-strike-next-scientists-virus-hunt-in-asia


Ecologist David Hayman, then a graduate student at the University of Cambridge, spent time in the rain forest of Ghana, catching hundreds of fruit bats, to collect sera, since bats carry a huge number of viruses in their blood. When Hayman took the blood samples back to the lab, some of the sera had antibodies against Ebola Zaire. The antibodies in the bat's blood meant the animals had once been infected with Ebola Zaire or something related to it. Hayman and his colleagues published the findings in the journal Emerging Infectious Diseases. That was July 2012, over 2 years ago. Now, it is thought that bats likely triggered the entire Ebola epidemic in West Africa.

Ecologist Kevin Olival, at EcoHealth Alliance in New York City, while studying another viral outbreak, had found bats in Bangladesh with antibodies to something related to Ebola Zaire. Olival and his colleagues published these findings in Feb 2013. Then a few months later, another team reported evidence of the virus in China. The bats with these antibodies have a broad range, across south Asia Olival says. "These species are found all the way down into parts of Indonesia." The data suggest that Ebola Zaire, or something to which it is related, is far more widespread around the world than previously thought. "Now, there's no sign bats have infected people in Asia with Ebola Zaire. And antibody tests can't say if the virus in the bats was specifically Ebola Zaire or something related." ... -- more

[Byline: Michaeleen Doucleff]

